31 Sucronensi et Dtm’msi: Sucro, a river some distance S. of Saguntum, with a town called Sucro at its mouth, where a very great but indecisive battle was fought in 75 B.c. between Pompeius and Sertorius. This was the battle at which Sertorius declared he should have thrashed the boy (Pompeius) had not the old woman (Metellus) come up. Turia is a river lying about half-way between the Sucro and Saguntum, with the town of Valentia at its mouth. Here a great battle was fought between the combined forces of Metellus and Pompeius, and those of Sertorius (Plutarch, Sertor. 19).
